segments.text: Can you move some of these around as you edit them?
Of course.
You've got some topics that you wrote down.
Please share those.
It'll work that way, huh?
I'm hooked up.
I wanted to mention something.
You asked me about people that had supported me through these early years, and one I definitely wanted to mention was George Kunze.
because he was the graduate dean at that time.
And I'd be remiss if I didn't mention him.
And I've always been one Haskell that kind of said, the administrator's a nice figurehead, but if you can get along good with his secretary, you got the job half made.
And Jane Thompson was always one who would welcome me and listen and help me.
arrange whatever needed to be done to make it work well.
So I really wanted to mention Kunze.
In relation to Kunze, as far as you were concerned in program quality and development, what role did the graduate dean play?
You mean other than just strictly rubber stamping approval or disapproval, I think?
I think he did an excellent job of trying to minimize conflicts and overlaps.
That was the most important thing I saw.

And if he sensed that there would be a problem in those areas, he would set out to fix it by getting the competing or interested parties together and make sure that it was resolved before the full approval.
Now, he was an agronomist.
Yeah.
Did that was an advantage to those of you in agriculture?
Probably, I think so.
At one time, a lot of the administrative channels were controlled by agriculture or staffed by agriculture people.
Another thing I overlooked was in the early days of the department, it's kind of a little humorous thing.
I don't know if you're aware of this, but one of the first people I met when I got here was Lou Hodges.
I mentioned him earlier being our undergraduate advisor for many years.
And Lou had been an honor student at Rice.
His father's a faculty member there.
And he had written to A&M when he saw an announcement in the Houston Post, I think it was, of A&M creating this new department in park management.
And he wrote a letter up here to the admissions office saying that he would like to come for a graduate degree, but his handwriting has always been terrible.
And they sent it to Animal Science because they thought he was interested in a graduate degree in pork management, rather than park management.
So I thought that was kind of a cute thing.
Another humorous thing that struck me was you were asking about faculty jokes and tricks and things of that kind.
For years, we supported
Texas Tech with that Southwestern Park and Recreation Administration conference training conference up at Texoma Lodge and uh...

I would take a bunch of students upper level students and as many faculty as we could spare to go up there for that three or four days and eventually you know ran a good bit of the program but uh... our fellas
being Texans, outdoorsmen like to go fishing and one time I came back into the room and they were all there, we were having a little conference.
I went into the bathroom there
took a few minutes out, got up off the toilet and just let out a shriek and everybody convulsed with laughter because they had put about an 18 inch white bass in the toilet.
So we did have a certain amount of those practical jokes going on from time to time.
Something that's given me probably

A continuing pleasure over the last few years has been something that I was allowed to try here that was a real success and largely with the help of John Blackburn that taught here for about 14 years and is now director of community services down in Bryan.
He taught our facilities, park facilities and maintenance courses and when they were going to build the
baseball complex.
You may remember there used to be a farm caretaker on that property on little six acres there.
And I got upset.
with the fact that while they were building that complex, they had allowed the trucks and the diesel fuel storage tanks and stuff under those big oak trees over there.
And I said, you know, I don't know if it was somebody in the physical plant that I went and complained to, you're going to kill all those trees with that oil seepage around the tree roots.
At that time, I had an adjunct landscape architect on deferred duty here from the National Park Service named Dave Torello.
And with him, we developed a proposal to turn that little six acre grove, oak grove, into a park.
And the original idea was to make a place where the roads wound, a road wound through that oak grove

It matured from that or changed from that into the idea of getting the physical plant to let us have the south end of that parking lot and restripe it so that it would accommodate up to 60-foot mobile home coaches down the south end and up the east end of that, 44.
And then John Blackburn, when it was approved by the physical plant, John Blackburn took that plan

implemented it and this physical plant put in underground water and electricity for us and then Pat Olson gave us $5,000 to build a shelter with ice machines and coke machines and stuff and in the picnic facilities and that that little thing developed into a
probably one of the best public relations things that I know about on campus.
We ran it on a fee basis with a two-week maximum to stay there.
As I remember, it was $15.
And the idea was to make it available to parents and families that wanted to come to ball games, football games, baseball games, or to visit students here.
and give them a nice place to park this because we really haven't got a first-class RV park in town.
And we opened them up July 1st for reservations for the various weekends, kind of a first-come, first-served.
And I don't know how many letters we got that had a $20 or a $50 and one time a $100 bill
with a letter from these folks saying, this is the greatest thing A&M has ever done.
We appreciate so much being able to come and stay overnight and stuff like this.
After I retired, Bonickson, who was the first department head after me, said all of that kind of stuff, maintenance and facilities, was not college level activity.
our students had built this stuff so they were getting a lot of experience out of it.
But he said no, he didn't like that.
So he turned it back to the physical plant.

But every time I go around that corner on Welburn I get just a glow of personal satisfaction to see that and I've often thought sometime if it has to be after I'm dead I hope they put the L. Reed designation on that little corner because that's provided a lot of
pleasure for people that came to visit.
That's a splendid idea.
Well, I wanted to do another one with about 60 sites, RV sites over on the north side, closer to where the peach orchard used to be.
Feeling that was convenient to the football thing, too.
But the research park took that out, and then the airport entrance
did a lot of that too, because there weren't very many sites over there that were level enough to take a big, you know, who would have needed about eight acres.
Anyhow, the little one has worked and has been nice and convenient there.
The other thing I didn't mention was that I guess I was thirty-six, thirty-five or thirty-six when I came here to start this thing.
And because we had
early on these senior profs that were 15, 20 years older than I was, a lot of our grad students were older than I was, which was kind of an unusual thing.
Because we were turning out a lot of Ph.D.s initially that were mid-career and they'd either have
enough time in service with their agency to have a sabbatical or a semester off or a year off and probably their only opportunity to get a terminal degree.
That's my agenda.
I'm caught up with you again.
Let's see, who were the key departmental staff people that are worthy of
words of appreciation, secretaries, other key staff people in the department?
Do I need to name them by name?
Well, some of them will.
The first one probably sticks in my mind was Hazel Grubbs.
And her husband was in the physical plan.
And Hazel was a very good-looking woman.
I think was, I won't say a party girl, but enjoyed good times and good events.
And maybe our department was a little too prosaic for her because she went, who did she go eventually to work for?
She transferred to Jackie Sherrill?
I believe so.
And went as his department secretary before he left to go wherever it was, Alabama or Mississippi.
Mississippi State.
Yeah.
But Hazel did a lot of the initial organizing and setting up.
When I got there, I had to lobby long and hard to get her an electric typewriter.
There were, you know, it seems funny now, but I guess we are talking back 35 years, and we were into electric typewriters at Michigan State.
But not here.
And they told me, you should have been here just a few years ago.
We didn't hardly have any air conditioning on this campus.
And that wasn't air conditioning at MSU either.
But then we didn't have the climate that they had here.
It must have been intolerable to have that kind of a situation.
What about other departmental staff people, the implementers of policy?
We had such a tremendous number of people going through all with their own personalities and incarnations.
It's kind of hard to single them out, to ask who was doing what.
As you look back, given the clarity of hindsight, are there any missed opportunities for this program?
things that might have been done if we had known then what we know now?
I can probably think of several, given a moment.
One of the big disappointments to me was that when I came here there was an institute of natural biosciences, which is about as redundant as saying pizza pie.
And there was a movement with Lineweber and Schuster and Tier and I to develop that into an actual school.
of natural resources, which is comparable to those you mentioned, Cornell and Michigan State and so on, Ohio State.
Never could get that done.
Pretty difficult for four departments to overcome the doubts and fears of eight or nine other departments when you're carrying 30% of the votes.
And so we never were able to do that.
And without that visibility, it was just impossible to do.
And now they're doing it again, I noticed.
Over there, Bob Brown in wildlife is chairing a committee to develop a school.

And I think they're going to have the same difficulty we had, which is even as department heads, we wanted a school, but we didn't want to interpose a next higher level person between ourselves and the dean.
We wanted direct personal access to the dean, but we wanted still some figurehead that would
to coalesce these four departments into a unit.
I think if they're able to figure out how to do that, they'll probably get it done.
But it's... You know, I love this school.
I've spent my life here, my career here.
I'm loyal to it.
But I honestly think over the years, A&M has been its own worst enemy.
You probably haven't heard that from anybody else.
How so?
Where?
Well, I was pretty close at one time with Alexander, what was his first name, who was a vice president of TU.
Lou, I'll be with you in a bit.
Are you going to be around a while?
He and I were on a panel with the National Research Council doing a water quality study and they wanted a recreational input into the water study.
So we were at Woods Hole for a while and talking about the schools.
And I sensed a different flavor at Texas than here.
Maybe I was just beginning to be frustrated here.
I don't know.
The same thing happened with who?
I've lost the train of thought, Haskell.
missed opportunities, lost opportunities you were talking about.
Yeah, but between UT and here, I know.
We had for a while a Texas University fellow that taught in the Lyndon School, Lyndon Johnson School.
I team taught a course with him, a graduate course.
And so that was the
closest I ever became to understanding some of the internal philosophies of Texas University.

And it seemed like, and I can't remember his name, he was in our local Rotary Club after he moved over here, that the attitude, this is an oversimplification, at Texas was, hey, that's never been done, let's do it.
And the attitude here was, hey, that's never been done.
Is somebody forcing us to do that?
That's a pretty rotten non-Christian knock against my own school.
But time and time again, when something radically different was proposed, it seemed to be, well, is somebody pushing this?
Have we got to do this?
Or can we get along without it?
Do you remember any time when we lost a real key person from Recreation and Parks?
We had them and then we lost them.
Well, for a number of reasons.
We lost, we had a key person and he was a young man when he died, Frank Suggett that I mentioned.
that had been my department head at Michigan State.
He didn't want to be an administrator.
He fought against it.
And the dean wouldn't let him out of it.
He appointed me acting head as the youngest, most junior instructor at that time while I was working on my PhD, simply because he didn't want to report anymore.
And that's how I became so close to the dean up there.
who gave me a lot of advice about coming to A&M.
And then Suggett came down here.
And I hired Suggett here as the first full prof. And he came down here.
That helped me more than anything because being young and raw, I had two senior people a decade older than me to kind of soften this brashness.
And Claire Gunn and Frank Suggett were so excellent because they were polar.
Whatever one of them committed himself to first, the other one would take the opposite side.
And I had the advantage of weighing those two things because they would never agree on anything.
And the loss, we lost him?
We lost Suggett because he was a great extension man and he liked going out with these communities, Oliver and Goliad or wherever.
He'd go and talk to people.
He was...

uh... so smart in an unorthodox way of looking at things and he bought a motor coach and he'd take students out on field trips to see at first hand these things and he was driving back from one of those

and went to sleep at the wheel and in Caldwell he ran off the road and hit an entrance driveway culvert and rolled he laid there with a broken back all night until somebody found him in the morning and over that period of maybe a year
taking pain medicine and alcohol just took him down.
And finally, his wife and I had to commit him for a short period of time.
And he kind of wrote his life story while he was locked up there, but he died shortly afterwards.
And I think that was a real loss.
We hired another person, Neal Cheek,
who was one of the most intelligent people we ever had on the faculty.
He came as a full professor.
He was a structural sociologist.
He was also the most divisive man I ever had on the faculty because he would never take charge of anything, but he wanted to be the power behind the throne.
Invisible, but directing what I was going to

Decide deviously so he was always organizing Groups within the faculty to try and promote something that he wanted to have done, but he wouldn't come forward and Tell me what you know argue his own case and he finally left and that was I don't know if it was because of the department situation or because he Finally washed up his marriage with his wife and they split and then he left
So those were two real bright people that we lost in the department.
When you were getting ready to make an important decision and you wanted any kind of advice and counsel, to whom did you turn?
I tried to turn to the whole faculty, but if it was kind of a private thing, first of all, I think any administrator needs a sounding board.
Now who was your sounding board?
Lou Hodges.
Lou Hodges, partly because he'd been around so long, partly because he was initially as a young man very shy, and also because he was close-lipped and would keep a confidence.
But I think everybody needs somebody, either a wife at home or somebody in the department, that

you can just unload on and rant and rave and get angry and or seek sympathy or wisdom or something you know not necessarily a decision but just somebody to that'll listen to you and you always had direct entree to the dean's office oh yeah yeah and that was that was very good i presume yeah yeah well let's see uh shift to humor
Do you remember any time the students ever attempted any jokes or pranks in class?
Like in my class one day, a student wouldn't know if he was to turn his tickets in with his final exam.
And I said, tickets?
Tickets for what?
Well, exam tickets.
I said, what do you mean?
Last night, sir, a sophomore was over in our core dorm selling $5 tickets to take final exams, and I bought a ticket.
Do you remember any good bull like that, the students, anywhere?
Well, what are my initials?
LMR, right?
For years, the students behind my back, but never let me know it, was they'd call me Elmer.
I don't know if that was good or bad, but that was the code word for the department head.
When we were in the horse barn, and we were very close with our grad students and faculty, I taught a

graduate seminar on administrative style if you want to call it that you know conduct behavior whatever and I guess I really ragged the students and I always tried to be one of the bananas in the bunch okay but yeah you can't be Casco you know that there's a mantle of of
leadership that keeps people at a distance, even if you want to be friendly.
In fact, while we were in the horse barn, a big fellow by the name of Steve Smith came around the corner and ran into me, and we kind of both apologized at the same instant.
Our grad students were upstairs in that loft, in that horse barn, and he
apologized and turned on his heel and ran up the stairs and I heard him shouting to the other grad students as he ran up the stairs, I called him Les, I called him Les.
There was that little bit of familiarity that I guess wasn't used there.
But I had one student in that group and there were about 10 of them that were really close and thick.
Some were Texans, some were not, played golf a lot together.
And this particular guy has been head of, well, he's not now, but he was head of the University of Arizona department, A.J.
Haley, Arthur Haley, for about 14 years, and he built a real fine program out there.
Anyway, he's a black Irishman from some Quincy, Massachusetts, a suburb of Boston, I guess, and he's as Irish, black Irish as you can get.

irreverent as hell and I had been talking a previous seminar night about the importance of demeanor if you want to be regarded as well regarded in a meeting you you sit forward like you got a bad case of piles you don't slouch back and you know all this kind of stuff
And dress is important, and tie is important, and how you speak is important, and these things, not only the message you're carrying, but how you present it.
Well, the next seminar class, I came into the conference room we had, which held about 15 or 18 of these grad student guys, because at that time we were all male.
There was just a Twitter.
Everybody was Twittering.
And I looked around, what the heck is going on here?
And A.J.
Haley was dressed in the most god-awful costume that you ever saw.
I just can't describe it.
It looked like Hatfield and McCoy hayseed.
He had a big old floppy felt hat down here and a great big peacock feather in it.
I mean, he was just going to put me on.
And that's one of those times where it just brought down the house.
But we used that to pretty good effect.
There's another time, and this is not so funny, about the time that long hair was coming into fashion.
And one of the grad students I had, he was real bright, and I'd brought him down from the University of Michigan.
He'd finished a good master's there, and I wanted him to do a PhD with us.
And he came out with this long bearded thing.
And it happened that that semester he was redheaded and he had a red beard.
And he was really testing me and, you know, I can have hair if I wanted and you, you know, you can't do anything about it.
And so we were scheduling a symposium and bringing in a number of national people
as lead speakers in this thing, a spring symposium.
And so I was giving out assignments to different ones, who could go to the airport and pick up one plane load at a certain time and who would drive a car and who would do this and who would do that.
And this Jim, after all the assignments were made, he said, and what do you want me to do?
I said, I want you to stay out of sight.
He said, what are you talking about?
I said, I don't want you around these people looking like you do with that beard.
And he said, that's my prerogative to wear a beard.
And I said, it's my prerogative to decide that I don't want you around those people.
Well, I guess that's not very good of me to say that, but...
That's the way I felt.
I agree with you.
I agree with you.
Let's see.
Any personal experiences where you, particularly as a newcomer, had trouble pronouncing a Texas place or person or a name?
Yeah.
Yeah.
And I want to add another thing about that, too.
Well, the first thing I want to do is this young fellow that I hired as the first instructor, Carol Dowell, from
He had been community parks director in Bossier City and was now at LSU.
He came over and he took me on some of my early wanderings around Texas.
One day we decided to attend, we made arrangements to attend a bi-state meeting in Alexandria, Louisiana.
This was just a couple months after I'd been here.
took my big station wagon that I still had, drove out east across Conroe and Huntsville and Lake Livingston, cut and shoot.
First time I'd seen cut and shoot.
And we got over there somewhere in East Texas, decided to stop and get a drink, non-alcoholic.
